00:12:16,698 --> 00:12:17,358
Yes, so...

241
00:12:18,919 --> 00:12:21,841
I think when we started the project we had a very clear sense of

242
00:12:21,981 --> 00:12:23,603
what the player would be doing in the world.

243
00:12:23,663 --> 00:12:25,764
They would be walking around and interacting with things,

244
00:12:26,244 --> 00:12:29,107
and then talking about things as they interacted with them,

245
00:12:29,167 --> 00:12:31,648
and then as you walked to the next place you would be walking as you...

246
00:12:31,974 --> 00:12:34,055
Sorry, talking as you walk from point to point.

247
00:12:34,095 --> 00:12:36,416
That was kind of our core loop idea,

248
00:12:36,496 --> 00:12:38,737
was walk and talks and interaction plots.

249
00:12:39,177 --> 00:12:42,079
And then actually working out how to author that in Ink

250
00:12:42,159 --> 00:12:44,460
was about a year's worth of work.

251
00:12:45,140 --> 00:12:48,782
Because finding a pattern which allowed you to author it

252
00:12:48,882 --> 00:12:50,463
flexibly enough that you didn't have to,

253
00:12:50,923 --> 00:12:52,504
that you could do whatever you needed to do,

254
00:12:52,744 --> 00:12:54,865
but that wasn't so complicated that you had to

255
00:12:55,085 --> 00:12:56,586
constantly look up how to do it,

256
00:12:56,746 --> 00:12:58,006
or break it the whole time.

257
00:12:58,907 --> 00:13:00,147
Finding a right sort of balance.

258
00:13:00,487 --> 00:13:04,849
for scripting it, that was a really long and difficult iterative process.

259
00:13:04,889 --> 00:13:09,492
So I think we kind of had initial scripts within a couple of months, I guess,

260
00:13:10,972 --> 00:13:12,233
that did do that.

261
00:13:12,333 --> 00:13:17,076
They did the walking around and the talking, but they were a real pain to author.

262
00:13:17,116 --> 00:13:18,176
They were too fiddly.

263
00:13:18,216 --> 00:13:20,438
They were very, very fragile.

264
00:13:21,318 --> 00:13:25,140
And over the course of the project, we slowly worked out

265
00:13:26,101 --> 00:13:29,423
things that we were doing a lot of that we could extract into other ways.

266
00:13:29,483 --> 00:13:29,603
So.

267
00:13:31,427 --> 00:13:33,848
For example, the way the conversation in the game works.

268
00:13:34,428 --> 00:13:38,270
Originally, conversations were tied specifically to rooms and things we were looking at,

269
00:13:38,290 --> 00:13:39,791
because that's the easiest thing to do, right?

270
00:13:39,851 --> 00:13:42,192
You go to somewhere and you have a conversation about it.

271
00:13:42,973 --> 00:13:46,715
And what we have now is a system where they're walking around in an environment

272
00:13:46,755 --> 00:13:51,518
that the game is feeding conversation options in from a bank of conversation that it has all the time,

273
00:13:52,138 --> 00:13:55,740
which is triggered by the knowledge model that it's tracking in the game.

274
00:13:55,920 --> 00:13:57,341
So what you know and what you don't know.

275
00:13:57,865 --> 00:14:01,026
says well these conversations are relevant, these ones aren't, and all of that is sculpted in ink.

276
00:14:01,206 --> 00:14:02,246
All of that is crafted in ink.

277
00:14:03,026 --> 00:14:07,187
And yeah, it took a long time to build that structure and make it work.

278
00:14:08,368 --> 00:14:10,808
I can't remember what the question was now.

279
00:14:12,389 --> 00:14:18,391
It was a really complicated engine to build, but I think what we started with

280
00:14:18,611 --> 00:14:22,912
was a very clear idea that it ought to be possible to build this thing this way.

281
00:14:23,492 --> 00:14:25,553
We just had to find a pattern that allowed...

282
00:14:26,397 --> 00:14:31,358
the author, the human being writing it, not to get totally baffled by what they were doing.

283
00:14:32,839 --> 00:14:34,579
That's the major limiting factor.

284
00:14:34,739 --> 00:14:40,820
Right to the bottom level, because I mean right from the very early prototypes we had

285
00:14:40,840 --> 00:14:47,242
this idea that we could use the same text engine to basically not just produce prose

286
00:14:47,302 --> 00:14:50,382
as we did on 80 Days, but produce line by line.

287
00:14:51,488 --> 00:14:54,069
lines are basically an interactive film script.

288
00:14:54,429 --> 00:14:57,071
So each line is either a scene direction like

289
00:14:57,411 --> 00:15:00,293
show this camera shot, play this sound,

290
00:15:00,693 --> 00:15:04,255
play this kind of sequence or it's actual lines of dialogue.

291
00:15:05,556 --> 00:15:08,618
And then the engine takes these line by line

292
00:15:08,998 --> 00:15:10,920
and presents them in a visual way.

293
00:15:11,660 --> 00:15:14,182
And that never changed.

294
00:15:14,202 --> 00:15:16,963
We changed the high level structure quite a lot

295
00:15:16,983 --> 00:15:18,664
in order to fit the

296
00:15:19,692 --> 00:15:26,097
the continually evolving game design, but that general approach stayed consistent throughout

297
00:15:26,537 --> 00:15:32,301
even from right at the beginning when it was basically, it was almost a 2D game with like

298
00:15:32,421 --> 00:15:40,167
static comic book panels where you made dialogue choices in a kind of static 2D comic book

299
00:15:40,207 --> 00:15:42,089
panel and then it went from panel to panel.

300
00:15:44,050 --> 00:15:47,593
But fundamentally, you know, John was writing in the same way then as...

301
00:15:48,557 --> 00:15:54,660
he did towards the end, it's just that the whole game has changed in between.

302
00:15:55,180 --> 00:15:59,702
I guess when we're making this stuff we have a really, we have an ongoing discussion the

303
00:15:59,742 --> 00:16:03,963
whole time of what's in the game and what's in the ink, and we see those as two quite

304
00:16:03,983 --> 00:16:04,644
separate themes.

305
00:16:04,664 --> 00:16:09,586
So the ink is, should be in control of all the narrative stuff and all the presentation

306
00:16:09,606 --> 00:16:13,187
stuff and all the sequencing stuff and all the stuff that wants to be flexible depending

307
00:16:13,247 --> 00:16:14,808
on what the player might or might not have done.

308
00:16:17,744 --> 00:16:22,247
stuff that lets you, so that when you get to the end of the project you can redraft it,

309
00:16:22,447 --> 00:16:25,769
so that when you get to the end of the project you can make this particular line of dialogue not

310
00:16:25,829 --> 00:16:29,551
actually appear under that specific circumstance because that's the sort of thing that Ink's really

311
00:16:29,591 --> 00:16:35,996
good at. And then the game side has to cover all the things which are systemic, which we don't want

312
00:16:36,056 --> 00:16:41,379
to have to bother authoring specifically every time. So like when you're talking to another

313
00:16:41,419 --> 00:16:46,823
human being it drops into a two-shot which sort of goes over the shoulder between each character.

314
00:16:47,373 --> 00:16:50,535
And that's within the game code because you don't want the ink to have to worry about that.

315
00:16:50,555 --> 00:16:52,976
The ink doesn't even want to have to tell the game that that's happening.

316
00:16:52,996 --> 00:16:55,438
The game just goes, oh, two human beings are talking to each other.

317
00:16:56,198 --> 00:16:56,818
Time for a two-shot.

318
00:16:56,838 --> 00:17:00,200
Which is kind of exciting because you can just write a load of dialogue.

319
00:17:00,722 --> 00:17:02,503
without any scene instructions at all,

320
00:17:02,623 --> 00:17:05,703
and it will present it in an interesting way in the engine,

321
00:17:05,763 --> 00:17:08,884
which is kind of a magical process.

322
00:17:08,924 --> 00:17:11,384
What's really great about that is then I can take a dialogue sequence

323
00:17:11,404 --> 00:17:12,925
which was written for one location

324
00:17:13,045 --> 00:17:15,225
and pick it up and stick it in another location,

325
00:17:15,925 --> 00:17:16,745
and it will just work.

326
00:17:17,005 --> 00:17:20,626
And plenty of times in the game where you can have the same conversation

327
00:17:20,646 --> 00:17:23,647
with the same character in five, six different places in the world,

328
00:17:24,627 --> 00:17:26,127
just depending on how you happen to meet them,

329
00:17:26,147 --> 00:17:29,928
it doesn't really matter from our point of view at all.

330
00:17:30,763 --> 00:17:31,543
Yeah, that's super interesting.

331
00:17:31,583 --> 00:17:33,525
That's so cool.

332
00:17:33,565 --> 00:17:34,185
That's magic.

333
00:17:34,225 --> 00:17:35,126
That sounds like magic.

334
00:17:35,186 --> 00:17:35,986
I'm sorry.

335
00:17:36,326 --> 00:17:40,469
The idea that you can write a scene and then have the engine sort of programmatically figure

336
00:17:40,529 --> 00:17:46,533
out the shot, reverse shot of it, and then not worry about, like, from a direction perspective,

337
00:17:47,053 --> 00:17:47,713
that's so cool.

338
00:17:48,854 --> 00:17:49,174
Yeah.

339
00:17:49,194 --> 00:17:51,316
Well, it's incredibly liberating as well.

340
00:17:51,376 --> 00:17:54,257
And, like, obviously games like The Witcher do this.

341
00:17:54,277 --> 00:17:56,979
You know, games like Assassin's Creed Odyssey do this.

342
00:17:57,019 --> 00:17:59,080
They have programmatic two shots.

343
00:18:00,183 --> 00:18:05,965
they use to cover or like programmatic anims that are kind of brought in just to keep scenes

344
00:18:06,025 --> 00:18:08,865
alive when they haven't authored something specific to override it.

345
00:18:09,265 --> 00:18:12,326
And ideally you never notice that they're doing that, but I'm absolutely sure that they

346
00:18:12,386 --> 00:18:13,006
are doing that.

347
00:18:14,947 --> 00:18:19,327
We have the advantage of not having, because we don't have voice acting, we don't have

348
00:18:19,347 --> 00:18:25,229
continuous animation, we can cut between procedural stuff and scripted stuff incredibly fluidly

349
00:18:25,829 --> 00:18:27,749
without it being particularly noticeable.

350
00:18:28,689 --> 00:18:29,750
So we can really push that.

351
00:18:30,977 --> 00:18:32,859
It's a quite absurd extremes.

352
00:18:33,119 --> 00:18:34,280
So you can have the same...

353
00:18:35,100 --> 00:18:39,764
Yeah, you can have the same conversations with the same people in wildly different contexts.

354
00:18:40,664 --> 00:18:41,165
And the game...

355
00:18:43,246 --> 00:18:44,888
I'm curious, and before we move on to Greg,

356
00:18:45,088 --> 00:18:48,650
did this game's design and development influence the design and development of Ink?

357
00:18:49,511 --> 00:18:54,415
And if so, how has the language changed as a result of your work on Heaven's Vault?

358
00:18:56,428 --> 00:19:02,769
It's kind of stayed remarkably static. We've developed it over time, but most of the major advances that we made in ink

359
00:19:03,209 --> 00:19:07,650
happened at the very start of this project. It's been like one or two extra features that we've added.

360
00:19:08,111 --> 00:19:08,371
Yeah.

361
00:19:09,531 --> 00:19:14,452
It's worth noting that a lot of the design of Heaven's Vault comes from the design of Sorcery,

362
00:19:14,672 --> 00:19:16,752
despite the fact that they're very, very different games.

363
00:19:18,133 --> 00:19:23,054
A lot of what we're doing in Heaven's Vault is just taking something we prototyped in Sorcery and pushing it really, really far.

364
00:19:23,594 --> 00:19:26,235
So, of course, we had basic knowledge modeling and...

365
00:19:26,832 --> 00:19:30,657
scenes dropped in contextually if they happen to be relevant right now.

366
00:19:31,097 --> 00:19:32,979
Heaven's Vault evolved entirely after that.

367
00:19:32,999 --> 00:19:37,244
It's obviously used in specific places, but there were a few features like...

368
00:19:38,025 --> 00:19:38,265
Lists.

369
00:19:38,405 --> 00:19:39,246
Lists, yeah.

370
00:19:39,346 --> 00:19:46,074
Ink has a data structure called a list, which I think when you first pitched it I had no

371
00:19:46,174 --> 00:19:47,776
idea how powerful it was going to be.

372
00:19:48,490 --> 00:19:50,651
And you were like, well, it's sort of this and it's sort of that.

373
00:19:50,671 --> 00:19:51,891
And it sort of does both of those.

374
00:19:51,931 --> 00:19:53,192
And I was like, we don't need that.

375
00:19:53,232 --> 00:19:54,772
And you were like, yeah, but we can do it.

376
00:19:55,012 --> 00:19:57,993
And now, like, I build everything out of this thing.

377
00:20:00,034 --> 00:20:03,835
Programming speakers, basically they're enums or flags.

378
00:20:05,116 --> 00:20:07,256
But they're so much more powerful than that.

379
00:20:07,297 --> 00:20:10,077
They're kind of also a bit like mathematical sets.

380
00:20:10,318 --> 00:20:12,998
And the way we use it is for state tracking.

381
00:20:13,078 --> 00:20:14,959
So whether it's your inventory or...

382
00:20:15,385 --> 00:20:23,447
all of the things that you know about or whatever, and we just track kind of pools of these facts,

383
00:20:23,927 --> 00:20:29,848
essentially. Chris Remo did a talk at GDC this year about the fact system that they had in

384
00:20:30,128 --> 00:20:35,129
Firewatch. I only caught the second half of it, I need to catch up on the Vault, but

385
00:20:35,750 --> 00:20:38,410
I was going to entertain listening to it because we have a fact tracking system in

386
00:20:38,430 --> 00:20:41,011
Heaven's Vault which has something like three and a half thousand facts.

387
00:20:41,748 --> 00:20:43,929
And every single line in the game is sort of saying,

388
00:20:44,009 --> 00:20:45,770
do you know these facts, but you don't know these facts,

389
00:20:45,790 --> 00:20:47,190
in which case this line is appropriate.

390
00:20:47,290 --> 00:20:49,271
This is how the whole system works.

391
00:20:49,691 --> 00:20:50,111
Oh, yeah.

392
00:20:50,792 --> 00:20:51,452
That's a lot.

393
00:20:52,372 --> 00:20:54,813
It's fine, actually.

394
00:20:54,853 --> 00:20:55,914
It's very, very manageable,

395
00:20:55,934 --> 00:20:56,994
because they're all contextual.

396
00:20:57,435 --> 00:21:02,017
So you just look up ones that are relevant.

397
00:21:02,097 --> 00:21:02,697
Yeah.

398
00:21:03,217 --> 00:21:04,778
Definitely was a feature that we were building

399
00:21:04,818 --> 00:21:06,338
originally using quite a hacky system,

400
00:21:06,799 --> 00:21:08,479
kind of got wrapped into the language.

401
00:21:13,018 --> 00:21:16,540
I don't know if we all remember, it's been a journey, but this question started sort of

402
00:21:16,600 --> 00:21:22,324
out of a question about how you, how you sort of create the, how you, your process for writing

403
00:21:22,384 --> 00:21:23,304
the narrative of this game.

404
00:21:23,945 --> 00:21:26,647
Before we move on, I want to get the last part of CliftonB's question, because it was

405
00:21:26,667 --> 00:21:27,267
kind of interesting.

406
00:21:27,527 --> 00:21:31,950
They wanted to know, basically like they always have their narrative super solid before they

407
00:21:31,970 --> 00:21:33,091
start implementing.

408
00:21:33,411 --> 00:21:37,173
And they want to know, like, do you ever realize things you've missed after you've started

409
00:21:37,213 --> 00:21:38,554
implementing a storyline in your editor?

410
00:21:39,906 --> 00:21:41,127
How does that shape your game design?

411
00:21:41,147 --> 00:21:43,367
Whether it's a game like this or a game like 80 Days,

412
00:21:43,407 --> 00:21:49,090
like, how do you figure out what to incorporate in a game

413
00:21:49,150 --> 00:21:51,811
even when you're, say, six months from ship

414
00:21:52,071 --> 00:21:53,932
and you've already got most of the narrative written down?

415
00:21:54,292 --> 00:21:54,492
Like...

416
00:21:54,512 --> 00:21:58,854
Yeah, so the thing that the whole...

417
00:21:58,974 --> 00:22:00,634
So this business of building a structure

418
00:22:00,654 --> 00:22:03,296
where we write the ink and the game code processes it

419
00:22:03,736 --> 00:22:04,736
was very difficult,

420
00:22:04,776 --> 00:22:08,878
but the payoff for that is two weeks before we ship.

421
00:22:09,524 --> 00:22:12,005
I was playing through the game and I found a scene that I didn't like.

422
00:22:12,225 --> 00:22:13,186
I just didn't like it at all.

423
00:22:13,286 --> 00:22:14,386
The dialogue was rubbish.

424
00:22:14,826 --> 00:22:18,267
So I took half a day and I rewrote it entirely.

425
00:22:18,428 --> 00:22:20,768
Every single line of it was changed.

426
00:22:20,788 --> 00:22:22,809
The entire flow of that scene was changed.

427
00:22:23,629 --> 00:22:28,571
And I just took the file, rewrote it, tested it, swapped it out, and then it was in the

428
00:22:28,611 --> 00:22:29,772
game changed.

429
00:22:29,832 --> 00:22:32,013
Like, we were already in beta testing at this point.

430
00:22:32,113 --> 00:22:36,915
Like, we already, I think, had sent a code off of PlayStation's FQA process, you know.

431
00:22:36,935 --> 00:22:37,515
Dangerous.

432
00:22:37,855 --> 00:22:38,935
I didn't really like it.

433
00:22:39,407 --> 00:22:44,571
in the process, but it isn't dangerous because actually it's very easy to test a scene in

434
00:22:44,651 --> 00:22:47,853
isolation in ink and make sure that you're really very happy with it.

435
00:22:48,354 --> 00:22:51,176
And actually there's no cost to it.

436
00:22:51,276 --> 00:22:52,838
I don't need to talk to anyone else.

437
00:22:52,898 --> 00:22:56,360
I don't need to talk to the environment people or the character people or the animation people

438
00:22:56,440 --> 00:22:57,061
or anyone else.

439
00:22:57,481 --> 00:23:00,964
Like, I can just go off and do that on my own and come back with it and say, yep, that's

440
00:23:00,984 --> 00:23:01,244
better.

441
00:23:02,005 --> 00:23:05,127
And we constantly do that.

442
00:23:05,228 --> 00:23:07,850
So I think if Heaven's Vault has a good

443
00:23:08,306 --> 00:23:13,249
story or it has good characters or have good moments. It's not because we planned things

444
00:23:13,329 --> 00:23:17,532
cleverly in advance, it's because we planned something that was okay and we've got a really

445
00:23:17,572 --> 00:23:23,556
good system for trading up. So every scene in this game has been traded up to make it stronger or

446
00:23:23,636 --> 00:23:28,319
tighter or better. All the bits that we didn't need we cut and all the bits that could be

447
00:23:28,379 --> 00:23:33,042
stronger we developed. And the freedom to do that as a writer...

448
00:23:34,193 --> 00:23:37,856
Like film writers, script writers on films do this all the time.

449
00:23:37,896 --> 00:23:40,739
They are constantly rewriting screenplays on the day of shooting.

450
00:23:41,059 --> 00:23:42,720
That's normal in the film industry.

451
00:23:43,080 --> 00:23:46,243
In the games industry, you're supposed to lock your script six months in advance

452
00:23:46,703 --> 00:23:48,945
and still be happy with it by the time you ship.

453
00:23:49,005 --> 00:23:50,286
And that's a hell of an art.

454
00:23:51,086 --> 00:23:57,752
And yeah, breaking that assumption definitely comes with some compromises

455
00:23:58,192 --> 00:24:02,475
in terms of the fidelity of what we can achieve, but the payoff in terms of the...

456
00:24:03,212 --> 00:24:07,173
We're massively taking advantage of the fact that we're not fully voiced, we're not fully

457
00:24:07,193 --> 00:24:07,593
animated.

458
00:24:07,833 --> 00:24:08,393
So we're kind of...

459
00:24:28,396 --> 00:24:33,744
we're able to pour all of our energy into refining the core storytelling.

460
00:24:35,426 --> 00:24:37,549
It's a funny thing though, because people looking at it sometimes say,

461
00:24:37,609 --> 00:24:39,532
oh well it would have been nice if it would be fully voiced.

462
00:24:39,552 --> 00:24:41,795
But you go, you know what, actually, if it had been fully voiced,

463
00:24:42,296 --> 00:24:44,519
it would have been a significantly worse script.

464
00:24:47,103 --> 00:24:50,267
I also want to chime in on what fully voiced can mean for developers.

465
00:24:50,987 --> 00:24:55,432
Or from the player's side, fully voiced often means like I'm often sitting, I can't read

466
00:24:55,452 --> 00:24:58,575
the conversation at my own pace, I have to read it at the actor's pace.

467
00:24:58,996 --> 00:25:06,524
And often there's some very, very great, you know, performances in there.

468
00:25:07,645 --> 00:25:13,687
That like, I forget what I was playing. Oh yeah, it was Horizon Zero Dawn I was playing the other day and I was like resisting the urge to just keep

469
00:25:14,207 --> 00:25:20,870
uh, to just keep um, skipping past cutscenes because I wanted to, you know, hear the drama of it, but

470
00:25:21,390 --> 00:25:25,011
that's another thing that I don't think, I don't think, I don't hear it said aloud a lot, but like.

471
00:25:25,851 --> 00:25:31,293
Yeah, we're always talking about this and um, I think you know there are solutions,

472
00:25:31,353 --> 00:25:34,615
but the solutions are in the core game design. I kind of see that.

473
00:25:35,103 --> 00:25:39,645
