But to say that...

695
00:39:48,461 --> 00:39:50,903
I just read this one book and wrote the game is also not true.

696
00:39:50,923 --> 00:39:56,128
Like I know a ton of archaeologists. My dad is an anthropologist. I've met them all my life.

697
00:39:58,870 --> 00:40:04,595
Yeah, like it when you end up bringing together a lot of sources that you didn't deliberately look

698
00:40:04,635 --> 00:40:13,122
for because we chose to write this game for a reason, you know. And I think that goes

699
00:40:13,282 --> 00:40:16,105
across the team as well. Like Tom used to talk a lot about religion.

700
00:40:16,889 --> 00:40:20,071
Like that was something he was really interested in bringing to a sci-fi context and that's

701
00:40:20,111 --> 00:40:21,552
definitely fed through into the game.

702
00:40:22,232 --> 00:40:25,133
Right on.

703
00:40:25,914 --> 00:40:28,395
There are more questions in the chat that are very, very good, but I have one that I

704
00:40:28,415 --> 00:40:30,396
wanted to ask since the start, so I'm just going to throw it out there.

705
00:40:32,557 --> 00:40:34,899
How tricky was it to put this into a 3D context?

706
00:40:34,919 --> 00:40:38,861
This is your first 3D navigatable game.

707
00:40:39,581 --> 00:40:41,662
Tell me a bit about how that went for you because it must have been...

708
00:40:43,176 --> 00:40:48,657
tricky at best. Like, what engine and tools did you use to build these 3D worlds and like how did

709
00:40:48,677 --> 00:40:54,319
you end up deciding how to build them as these kind of quasi-3D storybook spaces that they came

710
00:40:54,379 --> 00:41:04,842
out as? So we built it in Unity and we basically started from the point of, as I said earlier,

711
00:41:04,902 --> 00:41:11,163
we wanted to make a 2D comic book essentially, but a dynamic interactive comic book.

712
00:41:11,434 --> 00:41:17,620
and what that would mean. And part of the reason we wanted to do that is because we loved

713
00:41:17,940 --> 00:41:23,505
2D character illustration because 2D character illustration can be really expressive.

714
00:41:24,906 --> 00:41:31,212
So we wanted to draw our characters from lots of different angles so that we could dynamically

715
00:41:31,272 --> 00:41:37,557
compose these panels and we constructed our environments in 3D. They were initially

716
00:41:38,108 --> 00:41:40,391
a lot simpler than the environment's theatre,

717
00:41:40,431 --> 00:41:42,933
because we wanted to create the sense of a background

718
00:41:43,353 --> 00:41:47,637
rather than construct entire worlds in 3D.

719
00:41:47,897 --> 00:41:49,179
But as we created this,

720
00:41:49,219 --> 00:41:52,041
and we created the main protagonist, Aaliyah,

721
00:41:52,341 --> 00:41:57,486
and we drew her from 12 different angles, her core pose,

722
00:41:57,706 --> 00:41:59,848
we just loved the overall effect

723
00:41:59,908 --> 00:42:01,550
of moving the camera around in 3D,

724
00:42:01,610 --> 00:42:02,971
because we created a...

725
00:42:03,967 --> 00:42:09,951
a system that basically has a database of character frames and depending on the camera's

726
00:42:10,192 --> 00:42:15,355
angle and certain tags that's been applied to her character, like whether she's in a

727
00:42:15,395 --> 00:42:22,960
particular walk or a talk or some emotion, then it would pick a different overall body

728
00:42:23,040 --> 00:42:28,264
frame and also paste a different facial expression over the top so we could get all of these

729
00:42:28,304 --> 00:42:28,984
different effects.

730
00:42:30,906 --> 00:42:32,867
And then yeah, the 3D basically...

731
00:42:33,573 --> 00:42:37,874
came out of that as we were experimenting with what you could do.

732
00:42:39,055 --> 00:42:43,716
Because we wanted it to initially just be 2D comic book panels,

733
00:42:43,756 --> 00:42:49,637
but then seeing the effect of all of that happening in 3D,

734
00:42:49,697 --> 00:42:52,858
we just thought it looked really cool.

735
00:42:54,158 --> 00:42:56,279
Interesting. I imagine...

736
00:42:56,979 --> 00:42:59,200
Did that change the way you did your sort of...

737
00:42:59,260 --> 00:43:01,220
how you structured the pace and flow of the game?

738
00:43:02,908 --> 00:43:07,131
How much of what you might call level design went into this game, and how did the decision

739
00:43:07,151 --> 00:43:09,953
to go full 3D change the way you structured it, if at all?

740
00:43:11,454 --> 00:43:20,680
I think it massively changed things, because as soon as you go full 3D, you get the ability

741
00:43:20,901 --> 00:43:27,005
to poke around in all of the little tiny corners of the level, just like any other 3D game.

742
00:43:28,065 --> 00:43:31,648
You've been through an evolution to get to that point, because at the beginning...

743
00:43:32,197 --> 00:43:36,038
We had a very limited amount of interactivity,

744
00:43:36,178 --> 00:43:39,719
in that it was kind of a visual choice-based narrative.

745
00:43:40,539 --> 00:43:42,420
So the narrative was really driving it.

746
00:43:42,440 --> 00:43:44,900
There was not so much exploration at all.

747
00:43:45,400 --> 00:43:50,341
You could only interact with whatever it gave you choices for.

748
00:43:50,881 --> 00:43:52,802
But as we opened it up,

749
00:43:53,042 --> 00:43:54,882
like we were talking for a while

750
00:43:54,922 --> 00:43:56,483
about having 3D environments,

751
00:43:56,543 --> 00:43:59,643
but maybe you have a completely fixed camera angle,

752
00:43:59,663 --> 00:44:01,684
a bit like a point-and-click adventure,

753
00:44:03,882 --> 00:44:08,266
...from that particular camera perspective, you could poke around these corners...

754
00:44:08,306 --> 00:44:09,868
...but it weren't fully interactive.

755
00:44:09,888 --> 00:44:12,510
As soon as you can swing the camera all the way around...

756
00:44:12,891 --> 00:44:17,235
...there is so much more scope for where you can go...

757
00:44:17,315 --> 00:44:21,178
...what you should be able to interact with because it's right there.

758
00:44:21,199 --> 00:44:23,721
That had an impact, right down into that!

759
00:44:24,430 --> 00:44:28,072
script because then suddenly your branching narrative script needs to be able to cope

760
00:44:28,092 --> 00:44:31,333
with the player who walks over to one side of the room and does one thing, walks over

761
00:44:31,353 --> 00:44:33,874
to the other side of the room and does another thing, then walks back to the first side of

762
00:44:33,894 --> 00:44:37,595
the room again, which is not a branching tree structure even slightly.

763
00:44:37,655 --> 00:44:39,215
It's something completely different.

764
00:44:39,556 --> 00:44:47,138
Because in sorcery, like when we have waypoints on the mini-maps, we can easily just say,

765
00:44:47,518 --> 00:44:50,759
we don't want you to go back in that room, so we'll just remove the choice to go back

766
00:44:51,080 --> 00:44:51,740
into that room.

767
00:44:51,920 --> 00:44:53,040
And we can directly.

768
00:44:54,193 --> 00:44:55,893
push the player in different directions.

769
00:44:56,153 --> 00:45:00,034
Like, depending on how open or friendly we want it to be,

770
00:45:00,134 --> 00:45:03,334
we can enable and disable choices to go in different directions,

771
00:45:03,435 --> 00:45:05,735
but we're always in control.

772
00:45:05,835 --> 00:45:08,315
Yeah, I mean, we do do that in Heaven's Lock.

773
00:45:08,355 --> 00:45:11,596
We will quietly turn a door off over here if you're way over there,

774
00:45:12,196 --> 00:45:14,316
but hopefully in a way that you never ever notice,

775
00:45:15,257 --> 00:45:17,157
but you lose a lot of that focus.

776
00:45:18,477 --> 00:45:20,678
So I think that you asked about level design,

777
00:45:20,698 --> 00:45:21,558
and I think that's a really good point.

778
00:45:21,733 --> 00:45:24,675
One of the things that really took me by surprise on the project was

779
00:45:25,255 --> 00:45:28,157
there was a point when I realised we actually needed to do level design

780
00:45:28,197 --> 00:45:30,938
and we needed to know what we were talking about with level design

781
00:45:30,978 --> 00:45:34,240
which we hadn't originally intended to be a thing that we needed to know.

782
00:45:35,681 --> 00:45:37,922
We were really lucky when we hired Laura Dilloway

783
00:45:37,962 --> 00:45:39,443
who's our lead environment artist.

784
00:45:39,463 --> 00:45:43,325
We've done some level design on LittleBigPlanetPSP amongst other titles

785
00:45:43,505 --> 00:45:47,708
and she was working at PlayStation at the same time as Walt.

786
00:45:49,718 --> 00:45:52,600
And so we ended up in a process where I would kind of write a scene and say,

787
00:45:52,620 --> 00:45:55,081
this is what I think the characters are doing in this scene.

788
00:45:55,121 --> 00:45:58,823
And this is roughly what I think the geometry needs to be like to make that work.

789
00:45:58,883 --> 00:46:02,745
And then she'd take it and turn that into more of a level design space,

790
00:46:03,086 --> 00:46:05,587
a space with better vistas and better lines of sight and things.

791
00:46:05,647 --> 00:46:09,509
And then I would take it back and say, well, I think we need to put more time in here.

792
00:46:09,549 --> 00:46:12,831
This bit's too quick, this bit's too slow, let's move around, that's too long.

793
00:46:13,311 --> 00:46:17,474
And between us, we could kind of thresh out a 3D space in a way that the narrative was happy,

794
00:46:18,402 --> 00:46:20,163
the 3D design of it was happy too.

795
00:46:20,323 --> 00:46:23,265
And actually, that process was brilliant.

796
00:46:23,826 --> 00:46:25,567
And I think one of the things that was really nice about it

797
00:46:25,667 --> 00:46:27,448
is that being a team of seven people,

798
00:46:27,808 --> 00:46:30,250
like, we just sat either side of a table,

799
00:46:30,270 --> 00:46:32,291
so the iteration time was incredibly fast.

800
00:46:32,832 --> 00:46:35,193
So we were just bashing geometry around between us

801
00:46:36,154 --> 00:46:37,435
and coming up with these spaces

802
00:46:37,535 --> 00:46:39,516
that kind of flowed in really interesting ways.

803
00:46:40,216 --> 00:46:43,258
I think that, yeah, that's...

804
00:46:43,672 --> 00:46:47,134
Something we hadn't expected to have to contend with, but actually it worked out really well.

805
00:46:47,394 --> 00:46:51,296
But as level design go, it's a fairly simple problem compared to something, you know, like

806
00:46:51,336 --> 00:46:54,658
a proper shooter game or an adventure game where you really have to think about all of those parts

807
00:46:54,698 --> 00:46:59,120
and all of those sightlines all the time. You do get a little bit more freedom in the way that

808
00:46:59,140 --> 00:47:03,982
the game is made. Yeah, that makes a lot of sense. We have about 10 minutes left, so if anyone has

809
00:47:04,002 --> 00:47:09,165
questions, please get them in now or forever hold them. There is a really good one.

810
00:47:09,632 --> 00:47:12,593
that will take us over into the archaeology system, if you have a minute,

811
00:47:12,853 --> 00:47:14,233
because I want to know how that whole thing works.

812
00:47:14,433 --> 00:47:19,115
And there's a good question here from devrsw, who wants to know,

813
00:47:19,155 --> 00:47:22,536
did you experiment with other difficulty modes around the translation stuff?

814
00:47:22,616 --> 00:47:25,277
I've been playing a lot, and I wish the game had fewer clues

815
00:47:25,697 --> 00:47:27,037
for those of us that love a challenge.

816
00:47:28,378 --> 00:47:32,919
Nope, just the right amount of clues, thank you, from someone who also loves a challenge.

817
00:47:34,099 --> 00:47:38,381
You went through about 20 prototypes of the translation mechanic.

818
00:47:39,887 --> 00:47:47,270
of all sorts of different mechanics and all sorts of different ways of solving that high-level design of decrypting hieroglyphs,

819
00:47:47,310 --> 00:47:49,771
which is the kind of thing we wanted to hit.

820
00:47:52,032 --> 00:47:59,014
And generally speaking, the window of good game design there is incredibly tight.

821
00:48:00,015 --> 00:48:04,276
Because if you make something which is too easy, where the player can brute force it,

822
00:48:04,336 --> 00:48:07,518
or they can just make random guesses, or they don't have to do any work,

823
00:48:07,578 --> 00:48:09,238
or there's no insight, or there's no structure.

824
00:48:09,575 --> 00:48:10,795
then there's actually nothing to do.

825
00:48:11,315 --> 00:48:12,896
And we had a lot of early prototypes

826
00:48:12,916 --> 00:48:14,977
where you just lobbed words into slots,

827
00:48:15,297 --> 00:48:16,678
and then eventually Aliyah would say,

828
00:48:16,698 --> 00:48:17,278
yeah, that's it.

829
00:48:17,578 --> 00:48:19,819
And you'd go, okay, that was a complete waste of time.

830
00:48:21,460 --> 00:48:23,521
But on the flip side of that,

831
00:48:23,561 --> 00:48:25,742
it's extremely easy to make a problem,

832
00:48:25,762 --> 00:48:26,722
which is far too hard.

833
00:48:27,022 --> 00:48:29,043
And in fact, the system we have right now,

834
00:48:29,163 --> 00:48:31,544
it's very, very easy for us to give you a translation,

835
00:48:31,584 --> 00:48:33,985
which is impossible for you to do.

836
00:48:34,866 --> 00:48:36,727
We just use the more complicated words in the language.

837
00:48:37,347 --> 00:48:39,448
And there's a lot of work that went into the game.

838
00:48:39,848 --> 00:48:43,189
to make sure that it never does that, or it very, very rarely does that,

839
00:48:43,629 --> 00:48:46,610
so that you don't just get translations that you have no idea about.

840
00:48:46,670 --> 00:48:48,490
Because then the player just disengages and says,

841
00:48:48,510 --> 00:48:50,110
well, I don't know, that could be anything.

842
00:48:50,730 --> 00:48:55,171
A bit like I used to do in French class, you know, I'd look at something and go,

843
00:48:55,811 --> 00:48:56,231
bof.

844
00:48:56,412 --> 00:48:56,932
And that was...

845
00:48:58,192 --> 00:48:59,212
Bad memory, sorry.

846
00:48:59,992 --> 00:49:01,412
...complex.

847
00:49:03,133 --> 00:49:03,913
Yeah, so...

848
00:49:06,273 --> 00:49:06,573
I think...

849
00:49:07,699 --> 00:49:10,641
If people are feeling confident about playing the translation game, then that's nice.

850
00:49:10,661 --> 00:49:16,085
And if people are feeling that they could do better with the translations in the game, then okay, fair enough.

851
00:49:16,225 --> 00:49:21,769
But language has a problem, which is that it does get arbitrary quite fast.

852
00:49:22,449 --> 00:49:26,372
Like, what a word happens to be is really just what it happens to be.

853
00:49:28,113 --> 00:49:35,439
So it's quite difficult to make a challenging language puzzle in the sense that you might mean it.

854
00:49:36,159 --> 00:49:36,579
Because...

855
00:49:37,334 --> 00:49:42,619
actually the challenging becomes basically random or impossible very, very quickly.

856
00:49:43,199 --> 00:49:45,862
And then it's not really fun at all.

857
00:49:46,242 --> 00:49:52,407
We definitely rather err on the side of, you know, without explicitly telling you what

858
00:49:52,447 --> 00:49:58,533
the words mean, just give you a great amount of clues to whether it's, you know, where

859
00:49:58,573 --> 00:50:02,977
it's written, what the symbols look like.

860
00:50:04,204 --> 00:50:08,485
or how a word relates to another word, whether there's similar symbols.

861
00:50:08,965 --> 00:50:13,106
If from that you intuit something quite easily, then I kind of feel like...

862
00:50:13,346 --> 00:50:13,906
That's a win.

863
00:50:14,026 --> 00:50:15,067
That's a win, exactly.

864
00:50:15,167 --> 00:50:18,748
Even if it feels slightly too easy, that's way better than the alternative.

865
00:50:18,908 --> 00:50:22,889
I think the other thing that people need to realise is that it's a 12-hour game,

866
00:50:23,609 --> 00:50:29,110
and by the end of the game there are long and complex and intricate words

867
00:50:29,150 --> 00:50:32,791
that you'll be looking at with deep, constructional reasons behind them.

868
00:50:33,571 --> 00:50:36,233
And the tutorial ramp is kind of gentle.

869
00:50:37,513 --> 00:50:38,894
That's probably for the best.

870
00:50:40,515 --> 00:50:48,079
So yeah, for people who want more challenges, I think there are plenty of challenges in

871
00:50:48,139 --> 00:50:54,023
there, even if it's just look back through all of your translations and even for ones

872
00:50:54,083 --> 00:50:58,685
where you know the words, can you work out why the word is the way it is?

873
00:50:59,782 --> 00:51:03,403
Like, what is the construction there? How are the symbols put together to form that word?

874
00:51:03,763 --> 00:51:07,284
Because there's a lot there to kind of decode.

875
00:51:07,464 --> 00:51:09,105
I mean, I think for us, like, the...

876
00:51:09,545 --> 00:51:12,086
You know, it was a very iterative process, and one where we...

877
00:51:12,506 --> 00:51:16,247
We settled on the translation mechanic after about a year and a half of work.

878
00:51:17,047 --> 00:51:21,148
And after we found it, and we really found it from experiments,

879
00:51:21,168 --> 00:51:23,649
we dug it out of the dirt, and we're like, wow, this works.

880
00:51:24,305 --> 00:51:27,266
And we tested it on so many people in so many contexts,

881
00:51:27,386 --> 00:51:31,068
and it's held up for two years or something for us as being,

882
00:51:31,588 --> 00:51:32,928
I'm pretty sure this is the one.

883
00:51:33,569 --> 00:51:37,230
Like, I look at it, and I honestly don't know

884
00:51:37,330 --> 00:51:39,111
how we could make it better at this point.

885
00:51:39,611 --> 00:51:44,833
Because, like, yeah, it's remarkable.

886
00:51:44,973 --> 00:51:46,894
Having seen the versions that didn't work,

887
00:51:46,954 --> 00:51:48,855
it's remarkable how well this version works.

888
00:51:48,915 --> 00:51:50,356
Whether you like it or not is up to you.

889
00:51:50,416 --> 00:51:53,017
But, oh my God, the other ones were a lot worse.

890
00:51:54,994 --> 00:52:00,918
Yeah, for sure. We're coming off to the end here. I always like to ask, and with this game more so than most,

891
00:52:02,159 --> 00:52:05,842
how did you get the word out about this game to people that you thought would enjoy it most? It's

892
00:52:05,882 --> 00:52:11,125
such a tricky game to sum up easily or to very quickly give someone a sense of what they will

893
00:52:11,145 --> 00:52:16,689
be doing. So how have you gone about marketing and sort of trying to get this game in front of people?

894
00:52:17,590 --> 00:52:20,612
Has it all been like YouTube, email, reviews? What's worked for you?

895
00:52:23,259 --> 00:52:29,743
Yeah, well, yeah, I mean, you know, step one is we have a PR agent who helps us in terms of like,

896
00:52:30,064 --> 00:52:38,090
she has a specific focus on adventure games and shows she has a good amount of contacts in that

897
00:52:38,170 --> 00:52:44,254
space, which helps. The other thing that helps is you write a really good game that everybody likes

898
00:52:45,655 --> 00:52:49,338
and then you email them saying, do you remember that game you liked? We've made another one.

899
00:52:49,478 --> 00:52:52,280
And I think that's pretty, pretty fundamental, actually.

900
00:52:53,294 --> 00:52:58,098
It's also taken us a long time to work out what the hook of the game is.

901
00:52:58,519 --> 00:53:06,246
We've been excited since the beginning about all the tonal aspects of the game, like characters, the world, the mechanics,

902
00:53:06,646 --> 00:53:11,771
but it took us a while to find out, purely through experimentation and talking to people,

903
00:53:12,271 --> 00:53:18,477
that it was the translation mechanic which really piqued people's interest.

904
00:53:18,797 --> 00:53:19,838
And so discovering that...

905
00:53:20,918 --> 00:53:24,601
Getting that down and always making sure that when we talked about the game,

906
00:53:24,962 --> 00:53:29,786
we made sure to mention we have an entire hieroglyphic language to decipher.

907
00:53:29,806 --> 00:53:32,789
That just became the thing that we always mentioned.

908
00:53:32,889 --> 00:53:35,872
Our one-line pitch for the game is an archaeological narrative adventure

909
00:53:35,892 --> 00:53:37,933
with an entire hieroglyphic language to decipher.

910
00:53:37,953 --> 00:53:39,655
Right, I've said that far too many times.

911
00:53:42,218 --> 00:53:44,159
and go, oh yeah, okay, a hieroglyphic language.

912
00:53:44,439 --> 00:53:46,340
But a lot of me wants to say, oh yeah,

913
00:53:46,560 --> 00:53:49,341
with this incredible, massively adaptive narrative

914
00:53:49,441 --> 00:53:51,222
that totally responds to everything you do

915
00:53:51,282 --> 00:53:52,442
that's completely non-linear,

916
00:53:52,482 --> 00:53:53,883
that lets you explore this massive,

917
00:53:53,903 --> 00:53:54,663
where are you going?

918
00:53:54,723 --> 00:53:55,643
Why have you come back?

919
00:53:55,743 --> 00:53:56,524
Why have you gone?

920
00:53:56,544 --> 00:54:01,046
And yeah, that's what carries the game.

921
00:54:01,106 --> 00:54:02,806
That's what, if you enjoy the game,

